# Create RFM features for customer segmentation
import datetime as dt

# Get the date of the last transaction in the dataset
last_date = df_clean['InvoiceDate'].max()
print(f"Last transaction date: {last_date}")

# Add one day to make sure all recency calculations are based on days *since* last purchase
analysis_date = last_date + dt.timedelta(days=1)
print(f"Analysis date: {analysis_date}")

# Group by CustomerID and create RFM metrics
# First, handle the returns (negative values) by focusing on successful purchases
df_pos = df_clean[df_clean['Quantity'] > 0]

# Create RFM dataframe
rfm = df_pos.groupby('CustomerID').agg({
    'InvoiceDate': lambda x: (analysis_date - x.max()).days,  # Recency
    'InvoiceNo': 'nunique',                                   # Frequency (unique invoices)
    'TotalAmount': 'sum'                                      # Monetary
}).reset_index()

# Rename columns
rfm.columns = ['CustomerID', 'Recency', 'Frequency', 'Monetary']

# Create a separate dataframe for returns information
returns_per_customer = df_clean[df_clean['Quantity'] < 0].groupby('CustomerID').agg({
    'InvoiceNo': 'nunique',       # Number of return transactions
    'TotalAmount': 'sum'          # Total return amount (will be negative)
}).reset_index()

returns_per_customer.columns = ['CustomerID', 'ReturnFrequency', 'ReturnAmount']

# Merge the returns information with the RFM dataframe
rfm = pd.merge(rfm, returns_per_customer, on='CustomerID', how='left')

# Fill NaN values in returns columns with 0 (customers with no returns)
rfm['ReturnFrequency'] = rfm['ReturnFrequency'].fillna(0)
rfm['ReturnAmount'] = rfm['ReturnAmount'].fillna(0)

# Calculate return ratio (interesting for segmentation)
rfm['ReturnRatio'] = rfm['ReturnAmount'].abs() / rfm['Monetary']
rfm['ReturnRatio'] = rfm['ReturnRatio'].fillna(0)

# Display summary statistics of RFM metrics
print("\nRFM Metrics Summary:")
print(rfm.describe())

# Visualize the distributions of RFM metrics
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(14, 10))

# Recency distribution
sns.histplot(rfm['Recency'], bins=50, kde=True, ax=axes[0, 0])
axes[0, 0].set_title('Recency Distribution (Days Since Last Purchase)')
axes[0, 0].set_xlabel('Days Since Last Purchase')

# Frequency distribution
sns.histplot(rfm[rfm['Frequency'] < 100]['Frequency'], bins=50, kde=True, ax=axes[0, 1])
axes[0, 1].set_title('Frequency Distribution (Number of Purchases)')
axes[0, 1].set_xlabel('Number of Purchases')

# Monetary distribution
sns.histplot(rfm[rfm['Monetary'] < 5000]['Monetary'], bins=50, kde=True, ax=axes[1, 0])
axes[1, 0].set_title('Monetary Distribution (Total Spend in £)')
axes[1, 0].set_xlabel('Total Spend (£)')

# Return ratio distribution
sns.histplot(rfm[rfm['ReturnRatio'] > 0]['ReturnRatio'], bins=50, kde=True, ax=axes[1, 1])
axes[1, 1].set_title('Return Ratio Distribution (For Customers with Returns)')
axes[1, 1].set_xlabel('Return Ratio (Return Amount / Purchase Amount)')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Step 1: Remove extreme outliers (keep customers with reasonable spending patterns)
rfm_filtered = rfm[(rfm['Monetary'] < 50000) & (rfm['Frequency'] < 100)]
print(f"Customers after filtering outliers: {len(rfm_filtered)} of {len(rfm)}")

# Step 2: Log-transform skewed distributions (Frequency and Monetary)
# Add 1 before log transform to handle zeros
rfm_filtered['LogFrequency'] = np.log1p(rfm_filtered['Frequency'])
rfm_filtered['LogMonetary'] = np.log1p(rfm_filtered['Monetary'])

# Step 3: Scale features for clustering
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Select and scale features for clustering
features = ['Recency', 'LogFrequency', 'LogMonetary', 'ReturnRatio']
scaler = StandardScaler()
rfm_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(rfm_filtered[features])
rfm_scaled = pd.DataFrame(rfm_scaled, columns=features)

# Let's visualize the correlation between our features
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(rfm_filtered[features].corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', vmin=-1, vmax=1)
plt.title('Correlation Between RFM Features')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Let's also visualize the scaled features
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(14, 10))
for i, feature in enumerate(features):
    row, col = i // 2, i % 2
    sns.histplot(rfm_scaled[feature], kde=True, ax=axes[row, col])
    axes[row, col].set_title(f'Distribution of Scaled {feature}')
plt.tight_layout()

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import dendrogram, linkage
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
import matplotlib.cm as cm

# Step 1: Determine optimal number of clusters using the Elbow Method
wcss = []  # Within-cluster sum of squares
silhouette_scores = []
max_clusters = 10

for i in range(2, max_clusters+1):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=42, n_init=10)
    kmeans.fit(rfm_scaled)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)
    
    # Calculate silhouette score
    labels = kmeans.labels_
    silhouette_scores.append(silhouette_score(rfm_scaled, labels))

# Plot WCSS (Elbow Method)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(range(2, max_clusters+1), wcss, marker='o')
plt.title('Elbow Method for Optimal k')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Plot Silhouette Scores
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(range(2, max_clusters+1), silhouette_scores, marker='o')
plt.title('Silhouette Score Method for Optimal k')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score')
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Based on the results, let's also try hierarchical clustering visualization
# Generate linkage matrix
Z = linkage(rfm_scaled, method='ward')

# Plot dendrogram - with corrected parameters
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plt.title('Hierarchical Clustering Dendrogram')
plt.xlabel('Customer Index')
plt.ylabel('Distance')
dendrogram(Z, truncate_mode='lastp', p=20, show_contracted=True)
plt.axhline(y=5, color='r', linestyle='--')  # Add a horizontal line for reference
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Implement K-means with k=4
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42, n_init=10)
rfm_filtered['Cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(rfm_scaled)

# Get cluster centers
cluster_centers = pd.DataFrame(scaler.inverse_transform(kmeans.cluster_centers_), 
                              columns=features)

# Count customers in each cluster
cluster_counts = rfm_filtered['Cluster'].value_counts().sort_index()
print("Number of customers in each cluster:")
for cluster, count in cluster_counts.items():
    print(f"Cluster {cluster}: {count} customers ({count/len(rfm_filtered)*100:.1f}%)")

# Calculate average RFM values for each cluster
cluster_summary = rfm_filtered.groupby('Cluster').agg({
    'Recency': 'mean',
    'Frequency': 'mean',
    'Monetary': 'mean',
    'ReturnRatio': ['mean', lambda x: (x > 0).mean() * 100],  # Mean and % with returns
    'CustomerID': 'count'
}).round(2)

# Rename columns for better readability
cluster_summary.columns = ['Recency (days)', 'Frequency (orders)', 'Monetary (£)', 
                          'Avg Return Ratio', '% with Returns', 'Count']
print("\nCluster Summary:")
print(cluster_summary)

Most recent purchases (31 days) Highest purchase frequency (8.8 orders) Highest spending (£3,802 average) 66% have made returns (indicates engagement with the brand)

Segment Description: These are your VIP customers - they shop frequently, spend significantly, and have made purchases recently. Their high return rate actually indicates engagement rather than dissatisfaction.

Cluster 0: Occasional Medium-Value Customers (46.1%)

Characteristics:

Moderately recent (55 days since last purchase) Low purchase frequency (2 orders) Medium spending (£598 average) Only 22% have made returns

Segment Description: These represent your average customers who shop occasionally but aren't deeply engaged with the brand. They're active but not committed.

Cluster 2: At-Risk/Churned Customers (22.6%)

Characteristics:

Very low recency (255 days since last purchase) Lowest frequency (1.4 orders) Lower spending (£396 average) 20% have made returns

Segment Description: These customers haven't shopped in a long time and are likely churned or at high risk of churning. They made few purchases before disappearing.

Cluster 3: Outlier (1 customer)

A single customer with extremely high return ratio (57) and very low activity.

Marketing Strategy Recommendations For High-Value Loyal Customers (Cluster 1):

Loyalty Program: Implement premium rewards for these top spenders Exclusive Access: Early access to new products and collections Personalized Recommendations: Based on their extensive purchase history Premium Customer Service: Dedicated support channels Referral Incentives: Reward them for bringing similar high-value customers

For Occasional Medium-Value Customers (Cluster 0):

Frequency Boosters: Incentives to shop more often (e.g., "Buy 3 get 1 free") Cross-Selling Campaigns: Recommend complementary products Engagement Content: More regular newsletters and product spotlights Mid-tier Loyalty Benefits: Encourage more consistent purchasing Special Occasion Promotions: Birthday offers, seasonal specials

For At-Risk/Churned Customers (Cluster 2):

Win-Back Campaigns: "We miss you" emails with significant discounts Feedback Surveys: Understand why they stopped purchasing Product Updates: Highlight what's new since their last purchase Last-Chance Offers: Time-limited significant discounts Remarketing Ads: Target them with visual reminders of your brand

Expected Business Impact By implementing these targeted strategies based on customer segmentation:

Increased Revenue: More personalized approaches should boost conversion rates Improved Retention: Better addressing the needs of each segment Reduced Marketing Waste: More efficient allocation of marketing resources Better Customer Experience: More relevant communications and offers Higher Customer Lifetime Value: Extending relationships through proper nurturing
